  "prompt": "How much does it cost to buy a flight simulator?",
  "response": "The cost of a flight simulator can vary widely depending on the type, complexity, and features you are looking for. Here are some general price ranges:\n\n1. **Home/Consumer Flight Simulators:**\n   - Basic setups with a joystick, throttle, and rudder pedals: $500 - $2,000\n   - Mid-range setups that include multiple monitors, better controls, and rudder pedals: $2,000 - $10,000\n   - High-end home setups with advanced controls, motion platforms, and VR headsets: $10,000 - $50,000+\n\n2. **Professional Flight Simulators:**\n   - Fixed-base simulators (non-motion, used for training): $50,000 - $200,000+\n   - Full-motion simulators (used by airlines and training centers): $1 million - $20 million+\n\n3. **DIY or Custom-Built Simulators:**\n   - Building your own simulator can be cost-effective if you source components individually. Costs can range from $1,000 to $50,000+ depending on the components and level of detail.\n\n### Key Components and Their Costs:\n- **Computer:** $1,000 - $5,000+ (depending on performance needs)\n- **Software (e.g., Microsoft Flight Simulator, X-Plane):** $60 - $120\n- **Flight Control Hardware (yoke, rudder pedals, etc.):** $200 - $2,000+\n- **Multiple Monitors or VR Headset:** $200 - $1,000+\n- **Cockpit Panels and Instruments:** $500 - $5,000+\n- **Motion Platforms:** $5,000 - $50,000+\n\n### Additional Costs:\n- **Accessories:** Head tracking, additional controls, etc.\n- **Maintenance and Upgrades:** Ongoing costs for updating software, replacing parts, etc.\n\n### Conclusion:\nFor a basic home setup, you might spend around $500 - $2,000. For a more comprehensive and high-fidelity experience, costs can easily exceed $10,000. Professional-grade simulators are much more expensive, often costing millions of dollars. Your budget and desired level of realism will greatly influence the total cost.",
